</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/umidibrell.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Midi Brell</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Traveller of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/17/00 11:44:19 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.animfactory.com/animgifs/creatures/animals3/dog/dogdrinking_sm_wht.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   good list</span><hr size=1> The enchanter spell rates are pretty much right on the money there.  Who knows about the items? Not me for sure =) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=copeland>Copeland</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/17/00 2:12:03 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haste percentages, the real numbers</span><hr size=1> Well, Nillon, I haven't read the stuff on that forum; Platt just asked to copy some stuff I wrote elsewhere.  But, I don't think you gave it that careful a read since you've made two errors in your assumptions.<br>
<br>
The first is assuming what the values represent--your values are incorrect <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> given the units of measurement that I always use when quoting haste values</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  It's akin to arguing with me that the speed limit is 55mph, not 88kph.  It's a meaningless argument given that 55mph equals 88kph.<br>
<br>
There are two ways to calculate haste.  Neither of them is right, neither of them is wrong...since they give the exact same results when you're done.<br>
<br>
One way is Damage Increase.  This is where you say &quot;Hey, I do 20% more damage per round with a weapon than before.&quot;  This approach has the advantage of indicating how much more damage you'll do over time.  <br>
<br>
The other way is Delay Reduction.  This is where you say &quot;Hey, this weapon is 17% faster.&quot;  This approach has the advantage of working with units everyone sees every day--e.g., a 20% haste makes a 50 delay weapon a 40 delay weapon.  Easy calculation.<br>
<br>
THOSE TWO STATEMENTS END UP MEANING THE SAME THING!!!!!! For example, take the age old debate:  is the FBSS 20% or 17%?  It's both...it just depends upon how you apply the haste value.  Do you do:<br>
<br>
DAM * 600/DLY * (1 + Haste) - in which case use 20%.<br>
<br>
Do you do:<br>
<br>
DAM * 600/(DLY * (1 - Haste)) - in which case use 17%.<br>
<br>
The numbers I quoted are Delay Reduction numbers because I like them better.  The numbers you quoted are Damage Increase numbers.  You're arguing apples against oranges.  As I've said before (and will probably say again), this is one of the biggest problems when folks just start saying &quot;Here are the definitive haste values for XXXX.&quot;  Without defining your terms, it's not really that useful.<br>
<br>
The second is--who ever said I used log parsing to get my results?  I think log parsing is terrible and only exceeded by watching the animations as a bad way of getting data.  <br>
<br>
Packet sniffers also suffer from deficiencies when it comes to reporting haste percentages.  They report theoretical values; they do not account for system-induced latencies.  And those latencies do exist as anyone who has done actual lengthy tests on hasting has seen.  On short tests, you won't see them, but on long tests of hundreds of swings you simply do NOT get the number of swings the packet sniffer would indicate you should; you get a lower number.<br>
 <p><font color=8bb4d2 face="Garamond"><b>- Cope -</b></font></p><i>Edited by <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=copeland>Copeland</A> at: 7/17/00 1:55:52 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=copeland>Copeland</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/17/00 2:43:03 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haste percentages, the real numbers</span><hr size=1> I just went over and checked Blades &amp; Fists to see what Platt wrote.  Those numbers did not come from the editorial on Hasting.  They appear to be taken from a beta version of the WeaponAnalyzer program....though, since he didn't post any explanatory text, I'm just guessing based upon the format.  <br>
<br>
I just checked the version that is currently posted publicly of that program and the numbers up there are ones I am happy with. <p><font color=8bb4d2 face="Garamond"><b>- Cope -</b></font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/uredspinebladeslinge.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Redspine Bladeslinge</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(8/3/00 12:40:37 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haste percentages, the real numbers</span><hr size=1> /bump<br>
<br>
Thanks for the info Nilon.  I knew ruff estimates, but it is always interesting to see where the haste items/spells come into play and % of increase.  I know that with FBSS and Alacrity I'm like a freakin blender <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/ujagriel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jagriel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(8/31/00 1:08:42 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haste percentages, the real numbers</span><hr size=1> Preliminary testing with a Sash of the Dragonborn from Howling Stones points to FBSS equivalent.  It MAY be a hair slower, the difference came up less than a second slower over a few minutes of testing, did this 4 times.  Anyway, it should be added to the list, and confirmed as soon as possible.<br>
<br>
Jag <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/ujagriel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jagriel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(8/31/00 1:14:33 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haste percentages, the real numbers</span><hr size=1> Based on Nillon's test friends and Goat's hard haste cap claims, do we know for certain that a hard cap exists?  I'd like to have confirmation from others, so all of us can communicate well with chanters/shaman on spell use, maximizing mana use.  I know for certain, using fbss/sash of the dragonborn haste (21 or 17 depending on which way you see it), that aanya's makes me faster than augmentation.  Still, Nillon most likely has a higher haste, so this may be possible in my particular case.<br>
<br>
Let's figure this out, or if it already has been, let's post it here for all of us to learn and utilize.<br>
<br>
Jag <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/ubrontothunderfoot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bronto Thunderfoot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Traveller of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(8/31/00 5:11:31 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haste percentages, the real numbers</span><hr size=1> Using a runebranded girdle, I dont notice much of a difference from a belt of virtue, which didn't seem much different from an FBSS.  I never really did any testing, but if there is a difference, it's not a very noticeable one. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/ujagriel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jagriel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(8/31/00 8:07:37 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Haste percentages, the real numbers</span><hr size=1> Just to clarify, it isn't so much IF the hard cap exists, but rather a firm confirmation on WHAT it is.<br>
